1.c: Encroachment of business and industry.
1.b: Convenient to places of employment and center of city.

areaDesc.5: This is a small and old section which has already felt the encroachment of business. A number of the larger singles have been converted into small apartments and boarding houses.

1.c: Age and obsolescence of structures.
1.b: Located conveniently.

areaDesc.5: An older section containing a mixture of small and moderate sized singles and a scattering of doubles. This area is popular with the skilled mechanic class.

1.c: None
1.b: Conveniently located with high elevation.

areaDesc.5: A slightly older section now inhabited by skilled mechanics employed in the nearby factories and railroads. There still continues the practice of converting large, old singles into two units. Streets are wide and shaded. There are a very few homes which will exceed the above range in prices and rents.

1.c: None.
1.b: Zoning restrictions, well landscaped streets and properties as well as convenient and pleasant locaiton.
1.a: High land rising steeply to the northwest.

areaDesc.5: This small area embraces approximately 60 large, modern and most attractive homes. They are owned by the city's wealthiest citizens and, since almost none have changed hands, price fluctuations are estimates only. Grounds are large and beautifully maintained.

1.c: Lack of sewers
1.b: Adjacent to places of employment.

areaDesc.5: An area of moderate sized workingmen's homes displaying fair pride of ownership. Home are detached and vary from bungalows to two-story.

6.1: Robin Wood District- Elmira Heights N.Y.

1.c: Smoke, dirt and noise plus necessity of having to cross railroad tracks.
1.b: Proximity to places of employment.

areaDesc.5: This is an area which is almost entirely surrounded by industry and business. Section is unrestricted and contains a mixture of cheap to medium priced singles and doubles. Children going to school must cross the railroad tracks.

1.c: Noise, dirt and general character of neighborhood as well as class of inhabitants.
1.b: Proximity to places of employment good transportation and central location.

areaDesc.5: This is an old portion of the city displaying absolutely no pride of ownership and giving the appearance of a slum area. Dwellings are built close together and many are in a dilapidated condition. Generally, more than one family occupied a single unit.

6.1: Central Negro & Foreign Section, Elmira, N.Y.

1.c: Subject to annual flooding. Normal drainage is poor.
1.b: None

areaDesc.5: A sparsely settled section along the banks of the Chenung River. Homes are of cheap bungalow and squatter type with an occasional two-story dwelling. There has been a tendency for institutional holders to demolish old, uninhabitable properties.

6.1: Lower East Side- Elmira & Waverly N.Y.

1.c: Lack of all city improvements and inconvenience of locaiton.
1.b: None

areaDesc.5: A sparsely settled area of small, cheaply built bungalows and shacks inhabited only by those who cannot afford to live elsewhere.

1.c: Lack of sewers and comparative narrowness of streets.
1.b: Pleasant location and room for development.

areaDesc.5: A somewhat newer section in which houses are small and rather cheaply built. Institutions do not care for this particular neighborhood and there has been a certain amount of dumping of their properties.

1.c: Intermingling of the old and new as well as lack of sewers beyond the city limits.
1.b: Adjacent to places of employment.

areaDesc.5: An area flanking industrial and business sections in which is found an intermingling of the old and the new as well as the small and fair sized dwellings. This neighborhood is the most popular among people of moderate means.

6.1: Central South Side- Southport & Elmira, N.Y.

1.c: No sewers and inconvenience of location.
1.b: Good transportation and room for expansion.

areaDesc.5: An outlying section, inconveniently located, but which is popular because of low values and rents. Dwellings are both small one-story and medium sized two-story.

1.c: Lack of all city facilities; cheapness of construction; noise from airport; dirt from factories and railroads.
1.b: Convenient to places of employment.

areaDesc.5: This is an area of small, cheaply constructed detached houses which is adjacent to an industrial section and traversed by two railroad lines. In the event of growth of the nearby Precision Tool Company, there are possibilities of an improvement in this neighborhood.

1.c: Subject to annual flooding. Normal drainage is poor.
1.b: None

areaDesc.5: This is a small area surrounding Miller Pond. Homes are of the cheap bungalow and squatter shack type with an occasional two-story dwelling. There has been a tendency for institutional holders to demolish old, uninhabitable properties.

1.c: Dampness from the river.
1.b: Convenient to city, industry and recreational grounds.

areaDesc.5: The best residential district of the south side containing a wide variety and mixture of large and small homes. A number of the former have been converted into two family units. Streets are shaded and properties well maintained.

1.c: Subject to annual flooding. Normal drainage is poor.
1.b: None

areaDesc.5: This is a sparsely settled area situated on both sides of Newton Creek. Homes are of the cheap bungalow and squatter shack type with an occasional two-story dwelling. There has been a tendency for institutional holders to demolish old, uninhabitable properties.

1.c: Age of dwellings and smoke form the railroads.
1.b: Conveniently located to places of employment.

areaDesc.5: An area of moderately priced singles popular with mechanics and railroad workers. Along Lake Street are found the higher priced singles and the majority of doubles.

1.c: Noise, dirt and general character of neighborhood as well as class of inhabitants.
1.b: Proximity to places of employment, good transportation and central location.

areaDesc.5: This section is made up of poorly maintained properties located in and around an industrial and railroad center. There is little apparent care in the upkeep of dwellings. This is, in effect, a slum area.

1.c: Age and obsolescence of dwellings.
1.b: Proximity to places of employment and center of city.

areaDesc.5: This is an old section containing a mixture of cheap to medium priced singles and doubles.

1.c: Age of structures and gradual transition to boarding houses and small apartments.
1.b: Proximity of business section and shaded streets.

areaDesc.5: An older section in which large, old singles predominate. A number of these have been converted into small aprtments and boarding houses. Unit in the four family command a higher rent since heat is furnished.

1.c: Smoke, dirt and noise plus necessity of having to cross railroad tracks.
1.b: Proximity to places of employment.

areaDesc.5: An area paralleling industry and the railroad yards. An unrestricted section containing a mixture of cheap to medium priced singles and doubles. Children going to school must cross the railroad tracks.

6.1: Railroad Yard Section- Elmira Hghts. & Elmira, N.Y.

1.c: Lack of sewers beyond city line.
1.b: Convenient for residents of Elmira Heights and those employed in adjacent reformatory.

areaDesc.5: The best residential section in Elmira Heights and one popular with the business men of that community as well as executives of the adjoining State Reformatory.

6.1: Oakwood Ave.- Elmira and Elmira Heights, N.Y.

1.c: Lack of sewers and churches.
1.b: Good transportation and room for expansion as well as marked pride of ownership.
1.a: Flat ground sufficiently high to escape danger of floods.

areaDesc.5: This is the second best residential section in the city and rates a high blue. Entire area contains a mixture of detached singles varying from small bungalows to fairly large two-story dwellings which accounts for the wide range in both prices and rents. One or two houses will even exceed the range given. Rear of property and a drop in topography separates this area from the adjoining one to the south.

1.c: Subject to river floods, cheapness of construction and lack of pride of ownership.
1.b: None

areaDesc.5: Originally, this was an area of small summer bungalows; a number of which have been converted for year round occupancy.
